##1.21-23 new coronary pneumonia in Wuhan (Part II)

Micro signal

Functional introduction, my individuality, is the historical narrative of the Times. I'm my own foreign land, and I'm trying 10,000 possible narratives.

On the afternoon of January 21, the three of US checked into a hotel in Wuhan's gold and Silver Lake, and quickly began to understand the situation. Two reporters went to the south China Seafood Market to find out the situation. While doing a telephone interview on the incident of Dr. Tao Yong Being Injured at Chaoyang Hospital in Beijing, I rushed to Wechat and asked a doctor friend in Wuhan. When the three of US first met in a hotel room, none of us wore masks, which seemed to make a big deal out of it. But when Wang Shan and Zhang Congzhi went out to interview a circle, two people wearing masks came into my room, "just saw the patient, we are afraid to infect you. ".

"where do you see patients? " I thought it was strange to see patients so easily. Isn't it an infectious disease?

"Even in the south China Seafood Market, even though the market was closed, some people were worried about their own shops and went back to see them. Many of them lived right next to the market. One of them brought us into the house. "

Then two reporters detailed the situation of this family. The man had just recovered from his illness and was discharged from hospital. When the woman, Li Guifang (not her real name) , became ill on January 11, the doctor said that she was not seriously ill and that she would come for an injection every day. The hospital patient already many, like her to go to the hospital to inject the patient every day many.

I feel more strange, Li Guifang to the Wuhan Red Cross Hospital is only a second-level hospital, usually people because there are fewer patients, see a doctor quickly and go. If this hospital has a lot of pneumonia patients, other hospitals won't be in good shape. When Li Guifang first went to see a doctor, the doctor and nurse wore only a mask. A few days later, the medical staff began to protect her from head to toe. Li Guifang's waiting time from the line to the infusion changed from 3 hours to 7 hours, and the number of patients was obviously very high.

Patients like Ms. Li were not quarantined. "Aren't these infectious agents of action? " I was surprised. The reporters also told the story of another interviewee, a 23-year-old patient who had just been discharged from the hospital. There are two things in this story that feel different from what the government told us at the time: First, the government told us that it was mostly middle aged and elderly people who were infected; second, until January 15, the Wuhan Health Commission had said that "no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission has been found" and later changed it to "the possibility of limited human-to-human transmission can not be ruled out, but the risk of sustained human-to-human transmission is low. ". The 23-year-old, who is in normal physical condition, has not been to the south China seafood market, but only recently cycled through it.

I also asked the reporter to verify the time when Li Guifang went to the hospital for the first time, January 11. Ten days have passed since January 11th, and these patients are walking around. What will it be like 10 days from now? How serious is the overall situation if reporters can go out and investigate and come up with information that surprises me so much?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
I quickly asked a doctor friend in Wuhan, Luo Xiaoli (not his real name) , where he is a tertiary hospital, he saw the situation is more serious. Originally we arranged to meet at noon the next day, to the next morning, Luo Xiaoli told me: really sorry, or not to see each other, worked for most of the doctor's life, may lose his job because of this matter.

His hospital, which has been treating pneumonia patients from the south China seafood market since late December, has been alerted by front-line doctors to a resurgence of "SARS" or similar diseases. But a doctor at their hospital was admonished for telling the story on Wechat. Luo said the admonition put pressure on doctors: Next, those who mentioned it in the hospital were criticized, and those who were more important had to sign confidentiality agreements. Luo Xiaoli was very helpless, "I have repeatedly told people in my extended family to wear masks and not to go out and have parties, but I can not tell you the case of pneumonia, only to duck and hide. If we had been able to warn our doctors more than 10 days earlier, it would not have come to this. "

On the night of January 21, Wang Shan contacted a virologist who had just arrived in Wuhan for a study trip. His voice had temporarily lost its voice due to illness. He urged us in words on Wechat, "LEAVE WUHAN AT ONCE! " He judged that the pneumonia epidemic in Wuhan was already very serious, almost to the state of war. Why had no one pulled the alarm? Wuhan failed to contain the virus in the early stages of transmission, soon causing widespread infection. He advised us to leave Wuhan and return home to isolate ourselves for two weeks.

I managed to persuade Luo Xiaoli to meet me briefly. At noon on January 22, I arrived at the entrance of the hospital. He said we should meet at another gate, but he repeatedly told me, "you shouldn't go through the hospital, even if you wear a mask. It's full of patients. Don't go through the hospital! "

We were at the hospital, a meter apart, talking, and he was wearing three masks, and I was wearing two. I thought he had been transferred to Concorde Hospital to support the pneumonia "front line" these days, he said, "where is the Concorde Hospital? We're on the front line here. I've got hundreds of possible patients here, and the test boxes are barely coming down, so it's hard to confirm. But this virus causes lung disease, which is completely different from other diseases, and it's clear from the CT,"I took a deep breath, fortunately, my family cancelled yesterday's birthday party. I do not know, only two kilometers away from my home ready to Party restaurant, this hospital pneumonia suspected patients, there have been hundreds of cases! It's a different world out there. I also think in almost everyone uses Wechat, Weibo, Douyin today, the whole society has no secrets to speak of. But a such a big emergency, like a large piece of ink immersed in white cloth, see people were wearing a strict "mask" , the public is still in carnival.

On the afternoon of January 22, the wechat account of Sanlian life weekly published the opening report of our Wuhan Pneumonia, "new type of pneumonia in Wuhan: Why didn't it get more attention until today? " The article quickly received a big response, as nearly 10 million readers read the article, they realized that Wuhan's pneumonia was clearly not getting enough attention to match its severity.

As a journalist with nearly 20 years of experience, I was struck by how easy it was to cover the story. Usually when we do in-depth research, the core information sources are difficult to access, but this time my feeling is that as long as someone goes to a hospital in Wuhan to have a look, talk to a doctor on the front line, talk to a patient in line, it is so obvious that the epidemic in Wuhan is raging crazily! It was like a pot of noodles about to boil. The fire was so hot that the foam layer quickly swelled and thickened and soon overflowed the pot. But there's just a thin layer of skin that holds the message, that makes the fact that almost everyone in the doctor community knows it, but it doesn't reach the public.

Let me feel a deeper layer of frustration is that we see, is not everyone has a cell phone, not everyone is busy to post micro-blog, micro-letter do? Why on January 23, before the sudden closure of Wuhan, the world of hospitals and the public world, the Chu River Han boundary? Is the medical profession, in our society, so voiceless? Are we living in an information society in 2020? Can the truth be hidden behind every phone, every mouth? So what are we busy expressing every day?
